    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 4, name: 'Coromega Omega-3 Squeeze Gummies', url: 'https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0COROMEGA' },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 5, name: 'Olly The Essentials Omega-3 Gummies', url: 'https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0OLLYOM3' },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 6, name: 'iwi Omega-3 Algae Gummies', url: 'https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0IWIALG' },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 7, name: 'Garden of Life Minami Omega-3 Gummies', url: 'https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0GOLOM3' },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 8, name: 'Barlean\'s Omega Swirl Gummies', url: 'https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0BARLEAN' },
  ],
};

const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Do omega-3 gummies work as well as fish oil capsules?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Omega-3 gummies can deliver DHA and EPA effectively, but most gummies provide significantly lower doses per serving compared to capsules. A standard fish oil capsule contains 500-1000mg of combined EPA/DHA, while most gummies provide 50-250mg per serving. To achieve the clinically studied dose of 1000mg EPA/DHA daily, you would need 4-20 gummies depending on the product. If you need therapeutic omega-3 doses for cardiovascular or inflammatory conditions, capsules or liquid fish oil are more practical. Gummies are best suited for baseline omega-3 maintenance.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is the difference between DHA and EPA?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'DHA (docosahexaenoic acid) and EPA (eicosapentaenoic acid) are the two biologically active forms of omega-3 fatty acids. DHA is the primary structural fat in the brain and retina, constituting 40% of polyunsaturated fatty acids in the brain. It is critical for cognitive function, memory, and neurological development. EPA is the primary anti-inflammatory omega-3, competing with arachidonic acid to reduce pro-inflammatory eicosanoid production. For brain health and cognitive support, prioritize DHA. For inflammation and cardiovascular health, prioritize EPA. Most experts recommend a supplement that provides both.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Are algae-based omega-3 gummies as effective as fish oil?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Algae-based omega-3 supplements provide the same DHA and EPA molecules as fish oil because fish accumulate their omega-3s by eating algae in the first place. A 2014 study in the Journal of the American Heart Association found that algal DHA raised blood DHA levels equivalently to fish oil DHA at the same dose. The advantage of algae-based supplements is sustainability and purity — they are free from heavy metal contamination risk, do not contribute to overfishing, and are suitable for vegans and vegetarians. The disadvantage is that algae supplements tend to be higher in DHA than EPA.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How much omega-3 do I need daily?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The American Heart Association recommends at least 250-500mg of combined EPA and DHA daily for general health maintenance. For individuals with documented cardiovascular disease, the recommendation increases to 1000mg daily. The National Institutes of Health sets the Adequate Intake for ALA (the plant-based omega-3 precursor) at 1.1g for women and 1.6g for men, but conversion of ALA to EPA/DHA is extremely inefficient (less than 5%), making direct EPA/DHA supplementation the preferred approach. Most Americans consume only 100-150mg of EPA/DHA daily from food.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Do omega-3 gummies have a fishy taste?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'High-quality omega-3 gummies should not have a noticeable fishy taste. Manufacturers use molecular distillation to purify and deodorize fish oil before incorporating it into gummies, and fruit flavors effectively mask any residual fish flavor. If your omega-3 gummies taste strongly of fish, the oil may be oxidized, which also reduces its effectiveness. Algae-based omega-3 gummies have no fishy taste whatsoever, making them the best choice for individuals sensitive to fish flavors.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can children take omega-3 gummies?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Omega-3 supplementation is widely recommended for children, as DHA is critical for brain development and cognitive function through age 18. Products formulated specifically for children typically provide 100-200mg of DHA per serving at appropriate doses for their body weight. The American Academy of Pediatrics supports omega-3 intake through diet (fatty fish twice per week) or supplementation. Always choose products formulated for children rather than giving them adult omega-3 gummies, which may contain doses too high for smaller bodies.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'When is the best time to take omega-3 gummies?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Take omega-3 gummies with the largest meal of the day, ideally one that contains other dietary fats. Omega-3 fatty acids are fat-soluble and absorb significantly better when consumed with dietary fat. A 2019 study in the Journal of the Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics found that omega-3 absorption increased by up to 300% when taken with a high-fat meal compared to a low-fat meal or fasting state. The gummy format provides a small absorption advantage because the gummy matrix itself contains some fat.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is the difference between omega-3, omega-6, and omega-9?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Omega-3 (EPA, DHA, ALA) is anti-inflammatory and essential — your body cannot produce it. Omega-6 (linoleic acid, arachidonic acid) is pro-inflammatory in excess and also essential, but the standard American diet provides 10-20 times more omega-6 than omega-3. Omega-9 (oleic acid, found in olive oil) is non-essential because your body can synthesize it. The key health metric is the omega-6 to omega-3 ratio: the ideal is 2:1 to 4:1, but most Americans have a ratio of 15:1 to 20:1, creating a chronic pro-inflammatory state. Omega-3 supplementation helps correct this imbalance.' },
    },
  ],
};
