    <h2 id="why-omega3">Why Your Brain and Heart Need More Omega-3</h2>

    <p>Omega-3 fatty acids are not optional nutrients — they are structural components of every cell membrane in your body, with the highest concentrations in the brain (where DHA constitutes 40% of polyunsaturated fatty acids) and the retina. EPA and DHA regulate inflammation, support neurotransmitter function, maintain arterial flexibility, and modulate gene expression. Without adequate omega-3 intake, your body cannot perform these functions optimally, regardless of how well you eat in other respects.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">70%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">of Americans do not consume the <strong>minimum recommended 250mg of EPA/DHA daily</strong>, according to NHANES dietary intake data. The average American intake is approximately 100-150mg per day — less than one-third of what the American Heart Association recommends for basic cardiovascular protection.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The omega-3 gap is driven by dietary patterns: fewer than 20% of Americans eat fatty fish twice per week (the primary dietary source of EPA/DHA), and plant-based omega-3 sources like flaxseed and walnuts provide only ALA, which converts to EPA and DHA at less than 5% efficiency. Supplementation is the most reliable way to achieve adequate omega-3 status for the majority of the population.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="brain" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>DHA: The Brain Omega-3</strong>
        <p>DHA is the primary structural fatty acid in the brain and retina. It supports neuronal membrane fluidity, synaptic plasticity, and neurotransmitter signaling. Low DHA levels are associated with cognitive decline, depression, and ADHD. The brain preferentially accumulates DHA over all other fatty acids.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="heart" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>EPA: The Anti-Inflammatory</strong>
        <p>EPA competes with arachidonic acid (an omega-6) for cyclooxygenase and lipoxygenase enzymes, reducing the production of pro-inflammatory eicosanoids. Higher EPA intake is associated with reduced CRP levels, lower triglycerides, and decreased cardiovascular event risk. EPA is the primary omega-3 for heart health.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="leaf" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Fish Oil vs Algae</strong>
        <p>Fish accumulate DHA and EPA by eating algae — they do not produce omega-3s independently. Algae-based supplements provide identical DHA/EPA molecules without heavy metal contamination risk or environmental concerns. Algae supplements tend to be higher in DHA than EPA, making them ideal for brain-focused supplementation.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="warning" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>The Dose Challenge</strong>
        <p>Most omega-3 gummies provide 50-250mg of combined EPA/DHA per serving — significantly less than the 500-1000mg found in standard fish oil capsules. This is the primary limitation of the gummy format for omega-3 delivery. Choose gummies with the highest EPA/DHA content per serving, and take them with a fat-containing meal to maximize absorption.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A 2019 meta-analysis published in the <em>Journal of the American Heart Association</em> analyzed <strong>13 randomized controlled trials</strong> with 127,477 participants and found that omega-3 supplementation with EPA/DHA reduced the risk of myocardial infarction (heart attack) by 8%, coronary heart disease death by 8%, and total CHD events by 7%. The benefits were dose-dependent, with higher EPA/DHA intake producing greater risk reduction.</p>
      <cite>J Am Heart Assoc, 2019 — Meta-analysis of 13 RCTs (n=127,477)</cite>
    </div>

