    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Omega-3 Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do omega-3 gummies work as well as fish oil capsules?</summary>
      <p>Omega-3 gummies can deliver DHA and EPA effectively, but most provide 50-300mg per serving compared to 500-1000mg in capsules. To achieve therapeutic doses (1000mg+) with gummies, you would need multiple servings daily. Gummies are best for baseline omega-3 maintenance, while capsules are more practical for cardiovascular or anti-inflammatory doses.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between DHA and EPA?</summary>
      <p>DHA is the primary structural fat in the brain (40% of brain polyunsaturated fatty acids) and is critical for cognitive function and neurological health. EPA is the primary anti-inflammatory omega-3, reducing pro-inflammatory eicosanoid production. For brain health, prioritize DHA. For heart and inflammation, prioritize EPA. Most experts recommend supplements providing both.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are algae-based omega-3 gummies as effective as fish oil?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Algae-based supplements provide identical DHA and EPA molecules because fish accumulate omega-3s by eating algae. A 2014 study in the <em>Journal of the American Heart Association</em> confirmed equivalent blood DHA levels from algal and fish sources. Algae supplements are also free from heavy metals and ocean contaminants.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much omega-3 do I need daily?</summary>
      <p>The American Heart Association recommends 250-500mg of combined EPA/DHA daily for general health, increasing to 1000mg for those with cardiovascular disease. Most Americans consume only 100-150mg from food. ALA from plants converts to EPA/DHA at less than 5% efficiency, making direct EPA/DHA supplementation the preferred approach.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do omega-3 gummies have a fishy taste?</summary>
      <p>Quality omega-3 gummies should not taste fishy. Molecular distillation and fruit flavoring eliminate fish taste in well-manufactured products. If your gummies taste strongly of fish, the oil may be oxidized. Algae-based gummies have zero fishy taste by nature.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can children take omega-3 gummies?</summary>
      <p>Yes, omega-3 is critical for children's brain development. Use products specifically formulated for children at appropriate doses. The American Academy of Pediatrics supports omega-3 through diet or supplementation. Barlean's Omega Swirl is our top pick for families.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>When is the best time to take omega-3 gummies?</summary>
      <p>Take with the largest meal of the day containing dietary fat. Omega-3 absorption increases by up to 300% when consumed with fat compared to fasting. The gummy matrix provides a small built-in absorption advantage from its own fat content.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between omega-3, omega-6, and omega-9?</summary>
      <p>Omega-3 (EPA, DHA) is anti-inflammatory and essential. Omega-6 is pro-inflammatory in excess and overconsumed (15:1 ratio vs the ideal 2:1-4:1). Omega-9 is non-essential. Omega-3 supplementation helps correct the inflammatory imbalance created by the modern Western diet.</p>
    </details>

